{"type":"agent_end","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are council member C3 for AAR case arb-ex12-20260630145920. Use the Pi MCP proxy tool named `mcp` to call AAR tools. The Pi proxy exposes AAR tools with `aar_` prefixes.\n\nEvery `mcp` call must have exactly this shape: a `tool` string and an `args` string. Do not include `action`, `server`, or `connect`. Do not pass `args` as an object.\n\nFirst call `mcp` with `{\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}`. If it returns `state: waiting`, call the same tool again with the returned `after_version`, using an args string such as `{\"after_version\":3}`. If it returns `state: ready`, read the returned prompt, turn, limits, remaining time, attempts remaining, and opportunity id.\n\nReview the visible arbitration record and admitted evidence. Use MCP tool calls for `aar_get_case`, `aar_list_evidence`, `aar_stat_evidence`, and `aar_read_evidence_range` when exact contents or provenance matter. You may use Pi's ordinary local tools to organize and analyze the record, but your vote must rely on admitted record evidence and the arbitration record.\n\nWhen ready, call `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote`, vote `demonstrated` or `not_demonstrated`, and a concise rationale grounded in the record. The `args` value must be a JSON string, for example `{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\"}`. The AAR prompt and tool list use unprefixed names such as `submit_council_vote`; in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`. Do not write tool-call markup as plain text. After `aar_submit_council_vote` returns `ok: true`, report that your vote was accepted and stop. Do not call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` again after your vote is accepted. If `aar_wait_for_opportunity` returns `state: done`, report that the case is done and stop. If it returns `state: failed` or `state: error`, report the returned message and stop. Do not ask the user for the next turn. Do not create a cron job. Do not listen for inbound HTTP.\n"}],"timestamp":1782832690964},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5eadabe23f434ceba9d089","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct-2507","usage":{"input":2405,"output":28,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2433,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782832690979,"responseId":"gen-1782832691-flZjKgwBo3jhErjfT4Qd"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_5eadabe23f434ceba9d089","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 21\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex12-20260630145920\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 891996\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"after_version\":21,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex12-20260630145920\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C3\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it must be proven with discipline. The proposition is not whether air travel around Iran became risky, whether airlines avoided Iran, or whether foreign states issued warnings. The proposition is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a qualifying, major, non-weather closure of Iranian airspace under this market’s rule.\\n\\nThe current case packet already fixes the legal test. The market-page record defines a qualifying closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately provides that a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports can qualify. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Limited cancellations, delays, airline-specific choices, foreign warnings, weather closures, or narrow partial restrictions do not decide this market.\\n\\nThat framing matters because it tells the council what evidence should count most. The rule identifies the primary resolution sources as official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files candidly state that no merits packet has yet been built. They point us to the same source classes that should decide the case: Iranian Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority records, public NOTAM material if available and attributable, airport-level operations records for the listed airports, and credible contemporaneous reporting that distinguishes an Iran-imposed commercial closure from airline rerouting, foreign restrictions, weather, or military-drill limits. Flight-tracking observations may corroborate operational effect, but they cannot by themselves prove who initiated the restriction or why.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is that the decisive evidence will show an Iranian-authority restriction, in force before the cutoff, that was imposed for non-weather security or military-tension reasons and was broad enough to satisfy the rule’s “major Iranian airspace region” or listed-airport standard. If official NOTAM or aviation-authority material shows that Iran suspended civilian or commercial flight permissions across a major portion of the Tehran FIR, and if credible reporting or airport records show that this affected commercial arrivals and departures at at least two covered airports before the deadline, the preponderance standard is met.\\n\\nThe present packet also identifies the main gaps and the likely defense. The unresolved-gaps file notes that the record does not yet preserve the relevant NOTAMs, official aviation notices, airport operation records, contemporaneous reporting, UMA rationales, or exact ET timing. It also flags the possibility that observed flight effects could have been caused by airlines or foreign governments rather than Iran, or that a restriction could have been too limited, regional, or exception-filled to qualify. Those are real weight issues. They do not defeat the plaintiff’s case at the opening stage, but they define the proof plaintiff must bring in the evidence phases.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case by asking five questions. First, is there an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act? Second, was it in force no later than May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET? Third, was the cause non-weather? Fourth, did it suspend or close commercial operations broadly enough across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two listed airports? Fifth, do official records and credible reporting corroborate the same account rather than merely repeating market chatter?\\n\\nPlaintiff expects to answer those questions with admitted source material, not speculation. The record already gives the rule, the burden, and the source hierarchy. The missing merits materials should be obtained and admitted next. If those materials show only a narrow, airline-specific, foreign-imposed, weather-related, or post-deadline disruption, plaintiff will not have carried the burden. But if they show an Iran-issued, non-weather NOTAM or equivalent official restriction that materially suspended commercial operations in the covered way before the cutoff, then the proposition is more likely true than not and the market should resolve for plaintiff.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the record presently proves the rule, not the proposition.\\n\\nThe proposition is not whether Iran was tense, whether traders expected disruption, whether aircraft rerouted, or whether some aviation notice may have existed. It is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure under this market's specific rule. Plaintiff bears that burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence narrows the dispute. The market-page file defines a qualifying event as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also allows a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. But the same rule excludes limited cancellations, delays, other partial closures, airline or foreign-government restrictions, and weather closures. Limited exceptions to a broad closure may be tolerated, but that does not erase the plaintiff's need to prove breadth, attribution, timing, and non-weather cause.\\n\\nThe other packet files are even more important for weight. The official-source-record, primary-evidence, and secondary-reporting files all tell us that no merits packet has yet been built. They do not contain an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization announcement, an authenticated NOTAM, airport operations records, a Reuters-style merits report about May 24, or a consensus of credible contemporaneous reporting. The unresolved-record-gaps file expressly says the packet does not yet preserve the relevant Iranian aviation records, NOTAMs, airport records, reporting, UMA rationales, source event, causation analysis, breadth analysis, or exact ET timing.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. Those missing links are the case. Flight-tracking patterns could show operational disruption, but they do not by themselves prove who initiated it. News or social-media claims could locate a lead, but they do not by themselves prove the exact notice, its legal effect, its exceptions, its airport coverage, or whether it was a countrywide, major-region, or merely limited regional restriction. Even an Iranian notice would still need to be read carefully: a western-sector restriction, daylight-only operating rule, requirement for fresh permissions, military-drill notice, VFR/general-aviation suspension, or airport-specific measure may be materially different from the market's required major commercial-airspace closure.\\n\\nThe council should therefore ask plaintiff to prove five things with admitted source material, not inference from market movement: first, an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act; second, effectiveness no later than the May 24 ET cutoff; third, a non-weather reason; fourth, qualifying breadth under the rule, including whether arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports were completely suspended if plaintiff uses the airport prong; and fifth, corroboration from the rule's preferred source hierarchy rather than circular reporting or screenshots of screenshots.\\n\\nThe defense expects the evidence phases to turn on exact source-chain work: the full NOTAM text if public, official Iranian aviation statements, airport-level operations records, credible reports that distinguish Iran-imposed restrictions from airline or foreign state decisions, and any contrary official statements that conditions remained normal or that no new broad notice existed. Provenance matters because this market's wording is precise and because partial aviation restrictions can look dramatic in headlines while falling short of the rule.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the fair conclusion is modest. Plaintiff may later find and admit decisive records. But the current record does not yet establish a qualifying closure. It establishes that the decisive official and corroborating materials are missing, and it preserves several reasons a disruption might not count: wrong actor, wrong scope, wrong airport coverage, wrong timing, weather, exceptions, or partial regional limits. Unless plaintiff fills those gaps with admitted evidence, the proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the merits evidence the opening identified as necessary. The proposition should resolve Yes under the preponderance standard.\\n\\nPX-1 gives the rule. A qualifying closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure. The rule also has a separate listed-airport suspension route, but plaintiff does not need to overstate that route here. The strongest proof is the major-region route: western Tehran FIR.\\n\\nPX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 all point to the same event. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region. It identifies the source as the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority and the instrument as NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. It further reports that all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR were shut, that only eight airports remained operational under daylight restrictions, and that fresh per-flight Civil Aviation Authority approval was required.\\n\\nPX-3 independently corroborates the core event. Gulf News reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight specific sites. That matters because it confirms both the government source and the aviation-operational nature of the restriction.\\n\\nPX-4 supplies the most precise timing and operational detail. It reports that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 was effective from May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30Z. May 22 at 20:46Z is May 22 at 4:46 PM Eastern time, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET cutoff, and the stated end time runs past the cutoff. PX-4 also reports that all prior operator permissions were suspended and that new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at affected airports. It describes the restriction as applying broadly to civil aviation activity in the western Tehran FIR, while preserving limited daylight operations at designated sites.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy each operative element. First, initiation: the evidence consistently attributes the NOTAM to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Second, timing: the restriction began May 22 and remained valid into May 25, covering the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather: none of the admitted reports describes weather as the cause. The stated context is military and security tension, possible U.S. strikes, operational needs, and the wider Iran conflict. Fourth, major breadth: the western portion of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reports describe closure or restriction of most western airports, suspension of civil flight permits or prior operator permissions, fresh CAA approval for passenger IFR operations, and commercial rerouting.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: provenance and limits matter. Plaintiff did not capture the official NOTAM itself, and the admitted reports describe exceptions. Some airports remained available in daylight, and the precise list of exceptions is not uniform across all reports. Those limits reduce the force of any argument that every listed airport was completely suspended. They do not defeat the major-region theory. The market rule expressly allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, and it does not require a nationwide closure if the closure applies generally to a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nOn this record, the better reading is that Iran did more than issue a warning or watch airlines make their own choices. Iran's aviation authority imposed a formal NOTAM restriction over western Tehran FIR, suspended existing permissions, required new CAA approvals for passenger operations, and left only limited daylight exceptions. That is an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major regional closure before the deadline. The proposition is therefore more likely true than not.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not pretend nothing happened. The record now shows a serious Iranian aviation restriction from May 22 to May 25. But plaintiff still has not proven the proposition as written: a major closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\\n\\nStart with what the admitted evidence proves. PX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 are secondary reports saying that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. They support attribution to Iran, a May 22 start, a non-weather security or operational context, and some real operational restriction in the western part of the Tehran FIR. D-X1, the raw NOTAM text as displayed by Notamify, largely confirms the timing and the core wording.\\n\\nBut D-X1 also shows the central limit. The raw Q-line is OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999, and the operative text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights on these airports. That is an airport/aerodrome closure notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice saying the Tehran FIR airspace, western Tehran FIR airspace, or transiting commercial routes were closed. The distinction matters because the market rule does not count every partial restriction. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports.\\n\\nPlaintiff's listed-airport route fails on this record. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. D-X1's raw exception list names OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW; among the listed market airports, only OISS/SYZ appears there. PX-2, by contrast, says IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN were among the airports that remained operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. Either way, plaintiff has not shown a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. The source list is internally inconsistent, and no airport operations records have been submitted.\\n\\nPlaintiff therefore relies on the major-region theory. That theory is closer, but the burden still matters. The best raw text in evidence speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not closure of the FIR's airspace. It preserves eight daylight exceptions and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA approval. PX-3 describes the measure as restrictions at most western airports and notes limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 calls it portions of airspace and affected airports, but again admits designated daylight operations. PX-2 is further downstream: it attributes key NOTAM details to Gulf News and does not reproduce the official NOTAM.\\n\\nD-X2 adds a contemporaneous conflict. Iran International reported that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flights were operating according to plan. That report also acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, so it does not erase D-X1. It does, however, undercut plaintiff's effort to turn an airport-specific western restriction into a proved countrywide or airspace-wide closure.\\n\\nProvenance also remains weak for a market whose rule names official Iranian aviation information as a primary source. Plaintiff candidly admits no official NOTAM database record or Iranian authority page was captured. D-X1 is a mirror, not the official source. The council can use it, but should give care to what it actually says: airport closures in part of a FIR, exceptions, daylight operations, and approval requirements.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, this record proves a limited but serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not more likely than not prove the rule's qualifying major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the proposition. It confirms the core plaintiff case.\\n\\nPX-R1, defendant’s Notamify raw-NOTAM mirror, is now the closest thing in the record to the NOTAM text. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 EST/estimated. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating only from sunrise to sunset. Most importantly, it says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nThat is not merely an airline choice, foreign warning, or market rumor. It is a formal Iranian CAA permission regime for civil passenger operations in the west part of the Tehran FIR, in force across the market deadline. That proves Iran initiation, timing, and commercial-flight effect more directly than plaintiff’s secondary reports alone did.\\n\\nDefendant’s scope argument asks the council to read the rule too narrowly. The rule is not limited to an enroute-only FIR closure. It covers a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Airport closures across the west part of Tehran FIR, plus suspension of all prior operator permissions and new CAA approval for civil IFR passenger flights, are a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that major region. The rule also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. The eight daylight exceptions therefore prove breadth with exceptions; they do not erase the closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need the separate listed-airport complete-suspension prong. Defendant spends time showing uncertainty about IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. That would matter if plaintiff’s only theory were complete suspension at two listed airports. It is not. The major-region prong independently resolves the case.\\n\\nPX-R2 also helps plaintiff once read carefully. Iran International reports a denial of a new notice limiting flights across the country. But it also states that the denial came after Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization said activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise to sunset. So PX-R2 rebuts a countrywide-overclaim; it does not rebut the western-FIR closure that satisfies the market’s major-region language.\\n\\nThe record now has consistent secondary reporting, defendant’s raw NOTAM mirror, and even defendant’s denial article acknowledging the earlier western-FIR suspension. The official-source gap affects weight, but the preponderance is clear: before the cutoff, Iran imposed a non-weather CAA restriction that broadly suspended civil passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR, with limited exceptions. That is a qualifying major closure under the rule.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal fairly identifies the strongest point for Yes: D-X1 proves a formal CAA permission regime for civil IFR passenger operations at western Tehran FIR airports. The defense accepts that. The remaining question is whether that equals the market rule's qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nIt does not, at least not by a preponderance on this record. The rule's limited-exception sentence matters only after plaintiff proves an otherwise broad closure. It does not make every airport restriction with exceptions into a closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nD-X1's exact wording is narrower than plaintiff's characterization. The Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope, and the E-line says \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except eight named airports. It then says new CAA permission is needed for civil IFR passenger flights \\\"on these airports.\\\" That is airport/aerodrome language. The record still lacks a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, barring commercial overflights, or suspending commercial flights transiting through the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff now disclaims reliance on the listed-airport prong, and rightly so: the record does not show complete suspension of arrivals and departures at two listed airports. That leaves only the major-region theory. But the evidence for that theory is still a mirror of an airport notice plus secondary reports. There are no airport operations records, no official Iranian authority page, no official NOTAM database capture, and no direct flight-permission dataset showing region-wide commercial suspension.\\n\\nD-X2 also matters in the narrow way the defense offered it. It acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, but reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions. That is not a knockout, but it is a warning against inflating a western airport-notice record into a broader airspace-closure finding.\\n\\nSo the record proves a serious, Iran-issued, non-weather airport restriction before the deadline. It does not prove the rule's major closure of Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The preponderance remains with No.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the closing question is not whether the record is perfect. It is whether the proposition is more likely true than not. It is.\\n\\nThe rule asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. The rule defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. That language is decisive.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence is now defendant’s own raw NOTAM mirror. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 estimated. That period begins before the deadline and extends beyond it. The text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except eight named airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then says all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and new permission had to be requested from CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nThat proves the essential points. The actor was Iran’s aviation authority: a CAA permission requirement imposed through a NOTAM. The timing was before and through the market cutoff. The cause was non-weather: the record places it in a security, military, and operational context, and no evidence suggests weather. The effect was major: across the west part of the Tehran FIR, all airports were closed except limited daylight exceptions, prior permissions were canceled for all operators, and civil passenger IFR operations required new CAA permission.\\n\\nDefense’s best point is that the NOTAM is framed as an airport or aerodrome closure, not an enroute FIR closure. But the market rule is broader than that. It does not require a pure overflight ban. It covers broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Commercial passenger flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except narrow daylight exceptions, and all prior permissions for civil IFR passenger operations are suspended pending fresh CAA approval, commercial flight operations in that major region have been broadly suspended.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong is not necessary. Plaintiff need not prove complete suspension at two named airports because the major-region prong independently covers this record. Defense’s focus on IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN therefore does not answer the core proof.\\n\\nNor does the Iran International article defeat the case. It denies a new countrywide airspace notice and reports normal conditions in that broader sense. But it also acknowledges the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension until Monday with limited sunrise-to-sunset operations. That is exactly why plaintiff has not argued a countrywide closure. The proposition is satisfied by a major Iranian airspace region, and the west part of Tehran FIR qualifies on this record.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the provenance limits: no official database capture was admitted, and Notamify is a mirror. But the mirror preserves raw NOTAM text, the secondary reports consistently corroborate it, and even the defense’s adverse report confirms the earlier western-FIR suspension. Against that, defense offers a narrower legal characterization, not a better factual explanation.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, Iran initiated a formal, non-weather, CAA-controlled suspension of civil passenger flight operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR before the cutoff, with only limited exceptions. Under the market’s own text, that is a major closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should decide Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is not that the May 22-25 measure was trivial. It was serious. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market proposition: a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace, within the rule, by the cutoff.\\n\\nThe record proves several points for plaintiff. D-X1 confirms a NOTAM-like text, A1010/26, effective before and through the cutoff. It connects the measure to Iran's CAA and a non-weather security or operational context. It shows real restrictions on civil IFR passenger operations at airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR. Those points should be accepted.\\n\\nBut they are not enough. The market rule is precise. A qualifying major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Separately, a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports qualifies. Plaintiff has abandoned the listed-airport route, and the record would not support it anyway: there is no operations record showing complete suspension at two listed airports, and the secondary reports conflict on which airports remained operational.\\n\\nSo everything turns on the major-region route. The best evidence for that route is D-X1, and D-X1 says something narrower than plaintiff needs. Its Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope. Its operative text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset. It then requires new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is an airport/aerodrome notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, suspending commercial overflights, or barring flights transiting the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says commercial flights arrive and depart through airports, so airport closures across a region should be enough. That is the strongest Yes argument. But the rule does not say any broad airport restriction counts. It says commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The word transiting is not surplusage, and the rule separately created a listed-airport prong for airport-specific complete suspensions. Reading an airport/aerodrome notice with daylight exceptions as an airspace closure collapses that distinction.\\n\\nThe limited-exceptions clause does not solve plaintiff's problem. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure once a broad closure is proven. They do not prove breadth by themselves. Here the exceptions are central: eight airports remained available sunrise to sunset, civil IFR passenger flights could occur with fresh CAA permission, and the evidence never supplies official operations records showing actual region-wide commercial suspension.\\n\\nProvenance also still matters. The primary source called for by the market is official Iranian aviation information. No official Iranian authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. The raw text is from a mirror. The corroborating reports are secondary, and their airport lists are inconsistent. D-X2 confirms an earlier western airport suspension, but also reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions, which counsels against overreading the measure.\\n\\nOn this record, the fair finding is that Iran imposed a formal, non-weather, western Tehran FIR airport restriction before the deadline. That may be close to the line, but plaintiff had to prove a qualifying major closure of airspace or a major airspace region. The decisive gap remains the same at closing: airport/aerodrome restrictions with exceptions are not proven to be the rule's major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and operative elements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource capture: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". URL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Headline: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks.\\n- Subheadline: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under daylight-only restrictions even as US Secretary of State Marco Rubio, speaking in New Delhi on Saturday, said Washington may have \\\"something to say\\\" on a possible Iran deal in the coming days.\\n- By Express Global Desk. 6 min read May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST. First published on May 23, 2026 at 09:05 PM IST.\\n- The article states that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighed fresh military strikes and mediators sought to revive US-Iran talks.\\n- It states that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, attributed to Gulf News.\\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational, including Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas; even at those airports flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority according to the NOTAM.\\n- It states that flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article describes the closure as a strong indicator that Tehran expected military action within days, not as a weather event.\\n- The article quiz section restates that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region; restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remained valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The quiz section also restates that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas, with daylight-only flights and fresh per-flight CAA approval.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured text extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM itself. The article attributes a key point to Gulf News and refers to the NOTAM but does not reproduce full NOTAM text.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News corroborating live update\\nSource capture: Gulf News, live article \\\"Trump says a deal with Iran and opening of Strait of Hormuz are 'largely negotiated'\\\". URL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:30Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Gulf News Report. Last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29.\\n- Live entry timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026.\\n- Entry heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- The entry states that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- The entry explains that NOTAM means Notice to Air Missions, an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The entry states that the move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- The entry states that it unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary live news page. It corroborates the existence, source, timing, and broad western-airport nature of the restriction, but does not reproduce the full NOTAM and includes the adverse limitation that limited daytime flights remained at eight sites and that officials cited operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Kenya Times detailed NOTAM timing and effect report\\nSource capture: The Kenya Times, \\\"Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window\\\". URL: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:08:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Article title: Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window.\\n- Author/date: by Jason Ndunyu, May 23, 2026.\\n- The article states that Iran closed portions of its airspace as reports emerged that the United States was preparing for potential military strikes while maintaining diplomatic signaling with Tehran.\\n- It states that, according to a newly issued Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), identified as OIIX A1010/26, all airports in the western portion of the Tehran Flight Information Region were closed to operations except for a limited number of facilities operating only during daylight hours.\\n- It states that the restriction was effective from Friday, May 22 at 20:46Z until Monday, May 25 at 08:30Z, applied broadly to civil aviation activity, and permitted only designated airports to operate between sunrise and sunset under strict conditions.\\n- It states that, according to the NOTAM, all prior operator permissions were suspended and new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at the affected airports.\\n- It states that the measure affected key regional airports while maintaining limited daytime activity at selected sites, including OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW.\\n- It states that, as of May 23, 2026, live Flightradar24 tracking showed a notable disruption in civilian air traffic over and around Iran following reports of the NOTAM, with visible flight paths bending around western, central, and eastern corridors and most aircraft diverting north, south, or further east.\\n- It attributes the timing of the restriction to U.S. military and intelligence officials adjusting posture in anticipation of possible developments involving Iran; it describes CBS reporting that the administration was preparing for a fresh round of military strikes but no final decision had been made as of Friday afternoon.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM. It provides the most detailed captured wording found in this investigation, including Zulu timing and airport-code exceptions, but plaintiff has not captured the official NOTAM database record itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 mirror showing airport-closure wording and exceptions\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X2 Iran International report on CAO denial and limited western-FIR suspension\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X3 Market rule and operative elements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] D-X4 Initial unresolved record gaps\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n- The May 24 market is captured as disputed in the Gamma API, but the packet does not yet preserve the UMA proposal texts or dispute rationales.\\n- The packet does not yet identify the event or report that caused the Yes proposal/dispute cycle.\\n- The packet does not yet preserve Iranian aviation authority records, NOTAMs, airport operations records, or contemporaneous credible reporting about the May 24 cutoff.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether observed flight cancellations or route changes, if any, were initiated by Iran rather than airlines or foreign governments.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether any closure was broad enough to qualify under the market rule, rather than a limited, regional, airline-specific, foreign, military-drill, or weather-related restriction.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve exact timing in ET relative to May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defense raw NOTAM mirror confirms west Tehran FIR airport closure and CAA permission regime\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Iran International report confirms earlier western Tehran FIR suspension while denying new countrywide notice\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-closure wording and exceptions\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S2 Iran International scope-conflict report\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S3 Market rule requiring qualifying major closure\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM A1010/26 (ev_09982b77bf9e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-09982b77bf9e)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `09982b77bf9e0e286f4a48c8acf9eb0a7b045c347babec5f61d3235fa31efa89`\\nBytes: 2847\\nRelevance: Credible secondary reporting identifying Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, its May 22-May 25 validity, western Tehran FIR scope, remaining operational airports, daylight limits, and per-flight approval requirement.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News live update on Iran western airspace restriction (ev_9f6b49a1ebfa_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-9f6b49a1ebfa)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\nSHA-256: `9f6b49a1ebfa2299a9bb316abddea1905ad902f9869e311efb954910336e9af0`\\nBytes: 1742\\nRelevance: Corroborating report that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites and possible military-exercise/security context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Kenya Times report with detailed NOTAM A1010/26 timing and affected airport codes (ev_47df93957e6e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-47df93957e6e)\\nSource: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/\\nSHA-256: `47df93957e6e97187f3df3ccc2010c24353530fc5f9b5c1ae893cbd3a2a132a8`\\nBytes: 2445\\nRelevance: Secondary report supplying detailed claimed NOTAM timing, airport-code exceptions, civil aviation scope, CAA approval requirement, and flight-tracking corroboration/adverse limits.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 text for OIIX western Tehran FIR airports (ev_342c71021810_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-342c71021810)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `342c71021810e497c6cbdb15471b672347336f282c814a93a94f56d7441f8bff`\\nBytes: 1271\\nRelevance: Provides the closest captured raw NOTAM wording found in defendant investigation, including NOTAM code, Q-line/aerodrome closure classification, effective period, western Tehran FIR airport closure language, exceptions, sunrise-to-sunset limit, and CAA approval requirement. Relevant to scope and whether the event was a broad airspace closure or airport-specific restriction with exceptions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: CAO denial of new countrywide NOTAM and normal flight conditions (ev_4c36e105a2b8_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4c36e105a2b8)\\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\\nSHA-256: `4c36e105a2b8b132be10b9565d835443d0d94971a416c40fea4d60042f9e56a1`\\nBytes: 1754\\nRelevance: Contemporaneous secondary reporting of an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson denial of a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions across the country's airspace, while acknowledging an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension with limited exceptions. Relevant to conflict, scope, and weight.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search ledger and weight assessment\\nPlaintiff searched exact NOTAM and source terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OIIX NOTAM, May 22 western Tehran FIR, Iran CAA/CAO western airspace, and May 24 cutoff terms. No official NOTAM database or Iranian aviation authority page was captured in this opportunity. Three secondary pages were captured and submitted: Indian Express, Gulf News, and Kenya Times. They consistently attribute a May 22-May 25 western Tehran FIR civil aviation restriction to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Weight limits: they are secondary; one attributes detail to another source; the full official NOTAM is not in the record; the reports describe exceptions/daylight operations and are best used for the major-region prong rather than a complete listed-airport suspension theory.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search ledger and weight assessment\\nDefendant reviewed the current evidence list and read plaintiff's three new submitted captures. Targeted searches used exact terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OITR OIKK, western Tehran FIR, and CAO denial language. Defendant found and submitted a Notamify raw NOTAM mirror and an Iran International contemporaneous denial/limitation report. No direct official Iranian aviation authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. Weight assessment: the raw mirror is probative but not official custody; it supports timing/formality while narrowing scope to airport/aerodrome closures with exceptions. The Iran International report does not negate the western airport suspension but conflicts with any broader countrywide or airspace-wide characterization.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal scope analysis\\nDefendant's evidence was read in full. The Notamify mirror confirms formal NOTAM A1010/26, May 22-May 25 timing, closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except limited daylight airports, suspension of all prior permissions for all operators, and a new CAA permission requirement for civil IFR passenger flights. Iran International denies a new countrywide airspace notice but confirms the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension. Rebuttal therefore focuses on the market rule's major-region language rather than the listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nDefendant inspected the record after plaintiff rebuttal. Plaintiff added no new source material and relied on defendant's existing D-X1/D-X2 exhibits. No additional outside source was needed because the rebuttal issue is the legal and evidentiary weight of the existing raw NOTAM mirror and Iran International scope report. The unresolved gap remains direct official-source custody and proof that the airport/aerodrome notice closed transiting commercial airspace or completely suspended listed-airport arrivals/departures.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":891996,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":21}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 21\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex12-20260630145920\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 891996\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"after_version\":21,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex12-20260630145920\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C3\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it must be proven with discipline. The proposition is not whether air travel around Iran became risky, whether airlines avoided Iran, or whether foreign states issued warnings. The proposition is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a qualifying, major, non-weather closure of Iranian airspace under this market’s rule.\\n\\nThe current case packet already fixes the legal test. The market-page record defines a qualifying closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately provides that a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports can qualify. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Limited cancellations, delays, airline-specific choices, foreign warnings, weather closures, or narrow partial restrictions do not decide this market.\\n\\nThat framing matters because it tells the council what evidence should count most. The rule identifies the primary resolution sources as official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files candidly state that no merits packet has yet been built. They point us to the same source classes that should decide the case: Iranian Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority records, public NOTAM material if available and attributable, airport-level operations records for the listed airports, and credible contemporaneous reporting that distinguishes an Iran-imposed commercial closure from airline rerouting, foreign restrictions, weather, or military-drill limits. Flight-tracking observations may corroborate operational effect, but they cannot by themselves prove who initiated the restriction or why.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is that the decisive evidence will show an Iranian-authority restriction, in force before the cutoff, that was imposed for non-weather security or military-tension reasons and was broad enough to satisfy the rule’s “major Iranian airspace region” or listed-airport standard. If official NOTAM or aviation-authority material shows that Iran suspended civilian or commercial flight permissions across a major portion of the Tehran FIR, and if credible reporting or airport records show that this affected commercial arrivals and departures at at least two covered airports before the deadline, the preponderance standard is met.\\n\\nThe present packet also identifies the main gaps and the likely defense. The unresolved-gaps file notes that the record does not yet preserve the relevant NOTAMs, official aviation notices, airport operation records, contemporaneous reporting, UMA rationales, or exact ET timing. It also flags the possibility that observed flight effects could have been caused by airlines or foreign governments rather than Iran, or that a restriction could have been too limited, regional, or exception-filled to qualify. Those are real weight issues. They do not defeat the plaintiff’s case at the opening stage, but they define the proof plaintiff must bring in the evidence phases.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case by asking five questions. First, is there an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act? Second, was it in force no later than May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET? Third, was the cause non-weather? Fourth, did it suspend or close commercial operations broadly enough across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two listed airports? Fifth, do official records and credible reporting corroborate the same account rather than merely repeating market chatter?\\n\\nPlaintiff expects to answer those questions with admitted source material, not speculation. The record already gives the rule, the burden, and the source hierarchy. The missing merits materials should be obtained and admitted next. If those materials show only a narrow, airline-specific, foreign-imposed, weather-related, or post-deadline disruption, plaintiff will not have carried the burden. But if they show an Iran-issued, non-weather NOTAM or equivalent official restriction that materially suspended commercial operations in the covered way before the cutoff, then the proposition is more likely true than not and the market should resolve for plaintiff.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the record presently proves the rule, not the proposition.\\n\\nThe proposition is not whether Iran was tense, whether traders expected disruption, whether aircraft rerouted, or whether some aviation notice may have existed. It is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure under this market's specific rule. Plaintiff bears that burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence narrows the dispute. The market-page file defines a qualifying event as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also allows a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. But the same rule excludes limited cancellations, delays, other partial closures, airline or foreign-government restrictions, and weather closures. Limited exceptions to a broad closure may be tolerated, but that does not erase the plaintiff's need to prove breadth, attribution, timing, and non-weather cause.\\n\\nThe other packet files are even more important for weight. The official-source-record, primary-evidence, and secondary-reporting files all tell us that no merits packet has yet been built. They do not contain an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization announcement, an authenticated NOTAM, airport operations records, a Reuters-style merits report about May 24, or a consensus of credible contemporaneous reporting. The unresolved-record-gaps file expressly says the packet does not yet preserve the relevant Iranian aviation records, NOTAMs, airport records, reporting, UMA rationales, source event, causation analysis, breadth analysis, or exact ET timing.\\n\\nThat is not a technicality. Those missing links are the case. Flight-tracking patterns could show operational disruption, but they do not by themselves prove who initiated it. News or social-media claims could locate a lead, but they do not by themselves prove the exact notice, its legal effect, its exceptions, its airport coverage, or whether it was a countrywide, major-region, or merely limited regional restriction. Even an Iranian notice would still need to be read carefully: a western-sector restriction, daylight-only operating rule, requirement for fresh permissions, military-drill notice, VFR/general-aviation suspension, or airport-specific measure may be materially different from the market's required major commercial-airspace closure.\\n\\nThe council should therefore ask plaintiff to prove five things with admitted source material, not inference from market movement: first, an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act; second, effectiveness no later than the May 24 ET cutoff; third, a non-weather reason; fourth, qualifying breadth under the rule, including whether arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports were completely suspended if plaintiff uses the airport prong; and fifth, corroboration from the rule's preferred source hierarchy rather than circular reporting or screenshots of screenshots.\\n\\nThe defense expects the evidence phases to turn on exact source-chain work: the full NOTAM text if public, official Iranian aviation statements, airport-level operations records, credible reports that distinguish Iran-imposed restrictions from airline or foreign state decisions, and any contrary official statements that conditions remained normal or that no new broad notice existed. Provenance matters because this market's wording is precise and because partial aviation restrictions can look dramatic in headlines while falling short of the rule.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, the fair conclusion is modest. Plaintiff may later find and admit decisive records. But the current record does not yet establish a qualifying closure. It establishes that the decisive official and corroborating materials are missing, and it preserves several reasons a disruption might not count: wrong actor, wrong scope, wrong airport coverage, wrong timing, weather, exceptions, or partial regional limits. Unless plaintiff fills those gaps with admitted evidence, the proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the merits evidence the opening identified as necessary. The proposition should resolve Yes under the preponderance standard.\\n\\nPX-1 gives the rule. A qualifying closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure. The rule also has a separate listed-airport suspension route, but plaintiff does not need to overstate that route here. The strongest proof is the major-region route: western Tehran FIR.\\n\\nPX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 all point to the same event. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region. It identifies the source as the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority and the instrument as NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. It further reports that all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR were shut, that only eight airports remained operational under daylight restrictions, and that fresh per-flight Civil Aviation Authority approval was required.\\n\\nPX-3 independently corroborates the core event. Gulf News reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight specific sites. That matters because it confirms both the government source and the aviation-operational nature of the restriction.\\n\\nPX-4 supplies the most precise timing and operational detail. It reports that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 was effective from May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30Z. May 22 at 20:46Z is May 22 at 4:46 PM Eastern time, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET cutoff, and the stated end time runs past the cutoff. PX-4 also reports that all prior operator permissions were suspended and that new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at affected airports. It describes the restriction as applying broadly to civil aviation activity in the western Tehran FIR, while preserving limited daylight operations at designated sites.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy each operative element. First, initiation: the evidence consistently attributes the NOTAM to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Second, timing: the restriction began May 22 and remained valid into May 25, covering the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather: none of the admitted reports describes weather as the cause. The stated context is military and security tension, possible U.S. strikes, operational needs, and the wider Iran conflict. Fourth, major breadth: the western portion of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reports describe closure or restriction of most western airports, suspension of civil flight permits or prior operator permissions, fresh CAA approval for passenger IFR operations, and commercial rerouting.\\n\\nThe defense is right about one thing: provenance and limits matter. Plaintiff did not capture the official NOTAM itself, and the admitted reports describe exceptions. Some airports remained available in daylight, and the precise list of exceptions is not uniform across all reports. Those limits reduce the force of any argument that every listed airport was completely suspended. They do not defeat the major-region theory. The market rule expressly allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, and it does not require a nationwide closure if the closure applies generally to a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nOn this record, the better reading is that Iran did more than issue a warning or watch airlines make their own choices. Iran's aviation authority imposed a formal NOTAM restriction over western Tehran FIR, suspended existing permissions, required new CAA approvals for passenger operations, and left only limited daylight exceptions. That is an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major regional closure before the deadline. The proposition is therefore more likely true than not.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not pretend nothing happened. The record now shows a serious Iranian aviation restriction from May 22 to May 25. But plaintiff still has not proven the proposition as written: a major closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\\n\\nStart with what the admitted evidence proves. PX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 are secondary reports saying that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. They support attribution to Iran, a May 22 start, a non-weather security or operational context, and some real operational restriction in the western part of the Tehran FIR. D-X1, the raw NOTAM text as displayed by Notamify, largely confirms the timing and the core wording.\\n\\nBut D-X1 also shows the central limit. The raw Q-line is OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999, and the operative text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights on these airports. That is an airport/aerodrome closure notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice saying the Tehran FIR airspace, western Tehran FIR airspace, or transiting commercial routes were closed. The distinction matters because the market rule does not count every partial restriction. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports.\\n\\nPlaintiff's listed-airport route fails on this record. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. D-X1's raw exception list names OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW; among the listed market airports, only OISS/SYZ appears there. PX-2, by contrast, says IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN were among the airports that remained operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. Either way, plaintiff has not shown a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. The source list is internally inconsistent, and no airport operations records have been submitted.\\n\\nPlaintiff therefore relies on the major-region theory. That theory is closer, but the burden still matters. The best raw text in evidence speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not closure of the FIR's airspace. It preserves eight daylight exceptions and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA approval. PX-3 describes the measure as restrictions at most western airports and notes limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 calls it portions of airspace and affected airports, but again admits designated daylight operations. PX-2 is further downstream: it attributes key NOTAM details to Gulf News and does not reproduce the official NOTAM.\\n\\nD-X2 adds a contemporaneous conflict. Iran International reported that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flights were operating according to plan. That report also acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, so it does not erase D-X1. It does, however, undercut plaintiff's effort to turn an airport-specific western restriction into a proved countrywide or airspace-wide closure.\\n\\nProvenance also remains weak for a market whose rule names official Iranian aviation information as a primary source. Plaintiff candidly admits no official NOTAM database record or Iranian authority page was captured. D-X1 is a mirror, not the official source. The council can use it, but should give care to what it actually says: airport closures in part of a FIR, exceptions, daylight operations, and approval requirements.\\n\\nUnder a preponderance standard, this record proves a limited but serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not more likely than not prove the rule's qualifying major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the proposition. It confirms the core plaintiff case.\\n\\nPX-R1, defendant’s Notamify raw-NOTAM mirror, is now the closest thing in the record to the NOTAM text. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 EST/estimated. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating only from sunrise to sunset. Most importantly, it says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nThat is not merely an airline choice, foreign warning, or market rumor. It is a formal Iranian CAA permission regime for civil passenger operations in the west part of the Tehran FIR, in force across the market deadline. That proves Iran initiation, timing, and commercial-flight effect more directly than plaintiff’s secondary reports alone did.\\n\\nDefendant’s scope argument asks the council to read the rule too narrowly. The rule is not limited to an enroute-only FIR closure. It covers a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Airport closures across the west part of Tehran FIR, plus suspension of all prior operator permissions and new CAA approval for civil IFR passenger flights, are a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that major region. The rule also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. The eight daylight exceptions therefore prove breadth with exceptions; they do not erase the closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need the separate listed-airport complete-suspension prong. Defendant spends time showing uncertainty about IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. That would matter if plaintiff’s only theory were complete suspension at two listed airports. It is not. The major-region prong independently resolves the case.\\n\\nPX-R2 also helps plaintiff once read carefully. Iran International reports a denial of a new notice limiting flights across the country. But it also states that the denial came after Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization said activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise to sunset. So PX-R2 rebuts a countrywide-overclaim; it does not rebut the western-FIR closure that satisfies the market’s major-region language.\\n\\nThe record now has consistent secondary reporting, defendant’s raw NOTAM mirror, and even defendant’s denial article acknowledging the earlier western-FIR suspension. The official-source gap affects weight, but the preponderance is clear: before the cutoff, Iran imposed a non-weather CAA restriction that broadly suspended civil passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR, with limited exceptions. That is a qualifying major closure under the rule.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal fairly identifies the strongest point for Yes: D-X1 proves a formal CAA permission regime for civil IFR passenger operations at western Tehran FIR airports. The defense accepts that. The remaining question is whether that equals the market rule's qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nIt does not, at least not by a preponderance on this record. The rule's limited-exception sentence matters only after plaintiff proves an otherwise broad closure. It does not make every airport restriction with exceptions into a closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nD-X1's exact wording is narrower than plaintiff's characterization. The Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope, and the E-line says \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except eight named airports. It then says new CAA permission is needed for civil IFR passenger flights \\\"on these airports.\\\" That is airport/aerodrome language. The record still lacks a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, barring commercial overflights, or suspending commercial flights transiting through the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff now disclaims reliance on the listed-airport prong, and rightly so: the record does not show complete suspension of arrivals and departures at two listed airports. That leaves only the major-region theory. But the evidence for that theory is still a mirror of an airport notice plus secondary reports. There are no airport operations records, no official Iranian authority page, no official NOTAM database capture, and no direct flight-permission dataset showing region-wide commercial suspension.\\n\\nD-X2 also matters in the narrow way the defense offered it. It acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, but reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions. That is not a knockout, but it is a warning against inflating a western airport-notice record into a broader airspace-closure finding.\\n\\nSo the record proves a serious, Iran-issued, non-weather airport restriction before the deadline. It does not prove the rule's major closure of Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The preponderance remains with No.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the closing question is not whether the record is perfect. It is whether the proposition is more likely true than not. It is.\\n\\nThe rule asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. The rule defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. That language is decisive.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence is now defendant’s own raw NOTAM mirror. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 estimated. That period begins before the deadline and extends beyond it. The text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except eight named airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then says all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and new permission had to be requested from CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nThat proves the essential points. The actor was Iran’s aviation authority: a CAA permission requirement imposed through a NOTAM. The timing was before and through the market cutoff. The cause was non-weather: the record places it in a security, military, and operational context, and no evidence suggests weather. The effect was major: across the west part of the Tehran FIR, all airports were closed except limited daylight exceptions, prior permissions were canceled for all operators, and civil passenger IFR operations required new CAA permission.\\n\\nDefense’s best point is that the NOTAM is framed as an airport or aerodrome closure, not an enroute FIR closure. But the market rule is broader than that. It does not require a pure overflight ban. It covers broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Commercial passenger flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except narrow daylight exceptions, and all prior permissions for civil IFR passenger operations are suspended pending fresh CAA approval, commercial flight operations in that major region have been broadly suspended.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong is not necessary. Plaintiff need not prove complete suspension at two named airports because the major-region prong independently covers this record. Defense’s focus on IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN therefore does not answer the core proof.\\n\\nNor does the Iran International article defeat the case. It denies a new countrywide airspace notice and reports normal conditions in that broader sense. But it also acknowledges the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension until Monday with limited sunrise-to-sunset operations. That is exactly why plaintiff has not argued a countrywide closure. The proposition is satisfied by a major Iranian airspace region, and the west part of Tehran FIR qualifies on this record.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the provenance limits: no official database capture was admitted, and Notamify is a mirror. But the mirror preserves raw NOTAM text, the secondary reports consistently corroborate it, and even the defense’s adverse report confirms the earlier western-FIR suspension. Against that, defense offers a narrower legal characterization, not a better factual explanation.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, Iran initiated a formal, non-weather, CAA-controlled suspension of civil passenger flight operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR before the cutoff, with only limited exceptions. Under the market’s own text, that is a major closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should decide Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is not that the May 22-25 measure was trivial. It was serious. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market proposition: a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace, within the rule, by the cutoff.\\n\\nThe record proves several points for plaintiff. D-X1 confirms a NOTAM-like text, A1010/26, effective before and through the cutoff. It connects the measure to Iran's CAA and a non-weather security or operational context. It shows real restrictions on civil IFR passenger operations at airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR. Those points should be accepted.\\n\\nBut they are not enough. The market rule is precise. A qualifying major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Separately, a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports qualifies. Plaintiff has abandoned the listed-airport route, and the record would not support it anyway: there is no operations record showing complete suspension at two listed airports, and the secondary reports conflict on which airports remained operational.\\n\\nSo everything turns on the major-region route. The best evidence for that route is D-X1, and D-X1 says something narrower than plaintiff needs. Its Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope. Its operative text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset. It then requires new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is an airport/aerodrome notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, suspending commercial overflights, or barring flights transiting the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff's closing says commercial flights arrive and depart through airports, so airport closures across a region should be enough. That is the strongest Yes argument. But the rule does not say any broad airport restriction counts. It says commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The word transiting is not surplusage, and the rule separately created a listed-airport prong for airport-specific complete suspensions. Reading an airport/aerodrome notice with daylight exceptions as an airspace closure collapses that distinction.\\n\\nThe limited-exceptions clause does not solve plaintiff's problem. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure once a broad closure is proven. They do not prove breadth by themselves. Here the exceptions are central: eight airports remained available sunrise to sunset, civil IFR passenger flights could occur with fresh CAA permission, and the evidence never supplies official operations records showing actual region-wide commercial suspension.\\n\\nProvenance also still matters. The primary source called for by the market is official Iranian aviation information. No official Iranian authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. The raw text is from a mirror. The corroborating reports are secondary, and their airport lists are inconsistent. D-X2 confirms an earlier western airport suspension, but also reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions, which counsels against overreading the measure.\\n\\nOn this record, the fair finding is that Iran imposed a formal, non-weather, western Tehran FIR airport restriction before the deadline. That may be close to the line, but plaintiff had to prove a qualifying major closure of airspace or a major airspace region. The decisive gap remains the same at closing: airport/aerodrome restrictions with exceptions are not proven to be the rule's major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and operative elements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource capture: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". URL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Headline: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks.\\n- Subheadline: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under daylight-only restrictions even as US Secretary of State Marco Rubio, speaking in New Delhi on Saturday, said Washington may have \\\"something to say\\\" on a possible Iran deal in the coming days.\\n- By Express Global Desk. 6 min read May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST. First published on May 23, 2026 at 09:05 PM IST.\\n- The article states that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighed fresh military strikes and mediators sought to revive US-Iran talks.\\n- It states that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, attributed to Gulf News.\\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational, including Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas; even at those airports flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority according to the NOTAM.\\n- It states that flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article describes the closure as a strong indicator that Tehran expected military action within days, not as a weather event.\\n- The article quiz section restates that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region; restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remained valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The quiz section also restates that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas, with daylight-only flights and fresh per-flight CAA approval.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured text extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM itself. The article attributes a key point to Gulf News and refers to the NOTAM but does not reproduce full NOTAM text.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News corroborating live update\\nSource capture: Gulf News, live article \\\"Trump says a deal with Iran and opening of Strait of Hormuz are 'largely negotiated'\\\". URL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:30Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Gulf News Report. Last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29.\\n- Live entry timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026.\\n- Entry heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- The entry states that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- The entry explains that NOTAM means Notice to Air Missions, an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The entry states that the move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- The entry states that it unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary live news page. It corroborates the existence, source, timing, and broad western-airport nature of the restriction, but does not reproduce the full NOTAM and includes the adverse limitation that limited daytime flights remained at eight sites and that officials cited operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Kenya Times detailed NOTAM timing and effect report\\nSource capture: The Kenya Times, \\\"Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window\\\". URL: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:08:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Article title: Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window.\\n- Author/date: by Jason Ndunyu, May 23, 2026.\\n- The article states that Iran closed portions of its airspace as reports emerged that the United States was preparing for potential military strikes while maintaining diplomatic signaling with Tehran.\\n- It states that, according to a newly issued Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), identified as OIIX A1010/26, all airports in the western portion of the Tehran Flight Information Region were closed to operations except for a limited number of facilities operating only during daylight hours.\\n- It states that the restriction was effective from Friday, May 22 at 20:46Z until Monday, May 25 at 08:30Z, applied broadly to civil aviation activity, and permitted only designated airports to operate between sunrise and sunset under strict conditions.\\n- It states that, according to the NOTAM, all prior operator permissions were suspended and new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at the affected airports.\\n- It states that the measure affected key regional airports while maintaining limited daytime activity at selected sites, including OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW.\\n- It states that, as of May 23, 2026, live Flightradar24 tracking showed a notable disruption in civilian air traffic over and around Iran following reports of the NOTAM, with visible flight paths bending around western, central, and eastern corridors and most aircraft diverting north, south, or further east.\\n- It attributes the timing of the restriction to U.S. military and intelligence officials adjusting posture in anticipation of possible developments involving Iran; it describes CBS reporting that the administration was preparing for a fresh round of military strikes but no final decision had been made as of Friday afternoon.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM. It provides the most detailed captured wording found in this investigation, including Zulu timing and airport-code exceptions, but plaintiff has not captured the official NOTAM database record itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 mirror showing airport-closure wording and exceptions\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X2 Iran International report on CAO denial and limited western-FIR suspension\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-X3 Market rule and operative elements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] D-X4 Initial unresolved record gaps\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n- The May 24 market is captured as disputed in the Gamma API, but the packet does not yet preserve the UMA proposal texts or dispute rationales.\\n- The packet does not yet identify the event or report that caused the Yes proposal/dispute cycle.\\n- The packet does not yet preserve Iranian aviation authority records, NOTAMs, airport operations records, or contemporaneous credible reporting about the May 24 cutoff.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether observed flight cancellations or route changes, if any, were initiated by Iran rather than airlines or foreign governments.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether any closure was broad enough to qualify under the market rule, rather than a limited, regional, airline-specific, foreign, military-drill, or weather-related restriction.\\n- The packet does not yet resolve exact timing in ET relative to May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defense raw NOTAM mirror confirms west Tehran FIR airport closure and CAA permission regime\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Iran International report confirms earlier western Tehran FIR suspension while denying new countrywide notice\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-closure wording and exceptions\\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S2 Iran International scope-conflict report\\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S3 Market rule requiring qualifying major closure\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM A1010/26 (ev_09982b77bf9e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-09982b77bf9e)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `09982b77bf9e0e286f4a48c8acf9eb0a7b045c347babec5f61d3235fa31efa89`\\nBytes: 2847\\nRelevance: Credible secondary reporting identifying Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, its May 22-May 25 validity, western Tehran FIR scope, remaining operational airports, daylight limits, and per-flight approval requirement.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News live update on Iran western airspace restriction (ev_9f6b49a1ebfa_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-9f6b49a1ebfa)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\nSHA-256: `9f6b49a1ebfa2299a9bb316abddea1905ad902f9869e311efb954910336e9af0`\\nBytes: 1742\\nRelevance: Corroborating report that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites and possible military-exercise/security context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Kenya Times report with detailed NOTAM A1010/26 timing and affected airport codes (ev_47df93957e6e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-47df93957e6e)\\nSource: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/\\nSHA-256: `47df93957e6e97187f3df3ccc2010c24353530fc5f9b5c1ae893cbd3a2a132a8`\\nBytes: 2445\\nRelevance: Secondary report supplying detailed claimed NOTAM timing, airport-code exceptions, civil aviation scope, CAA approval requirement, and flight-tracking corroboration/adverse limits.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 text for OIIX western Tehran FIR airports (ev_342c71021810_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-342c71021810)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `342c71021810e497c6cbdb15471b672347336f282c814a93a94f56d7441f8bff`\\nBytes: 1271\\nRelevance: Provides the closest captured raw NOTAM wording found in defendant investigation, including NOTAM code, Q-line/aerodrome closure classification, effective period, western Tehran FIR airport closure language, exceptions, sunrise-to-sunset limit, and CAA approval requirement. Relevant to scope and whether the event was a broad airspace closure or airport-specific restriction with exceptions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: CAO denial of new countrywide NOTAM and normal flight conditions (ev_4c36e105a2b8_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4c36e105a2b8)\\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\\nSHA-256: `4c36e105a2b8b132be10b9565d835443d0d94971a416c40fea4d60042f9e56a1`\\nBytes: 1754\\nRelevance: Contemporaneous secondary reporting of an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson denial of a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions across the country's airspace, while acknowledging an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension with limited exceptions. Relevant to conflict, scope, and weight.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search ledger and weight assessment\\nPlaintiff searched exact NOTAM and source terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OIIX NOTAM, May 22 western Tehran FIR, Iran CAA/CAO western airspace, and May 24 cutoff terms. No official NOTAM database or Iranian aviation authority page was captured in this opportunity. Three secondary pages were captured and submitted: Indian Express, Gulf News, and Kenya Times. They consistently attribute a May 22-May 25 western Tehran FIR civil aviation restriction to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Weight limits: they are secondary; one attributes detail to another source; the full official NOTAM is not in the record; the reports describe exceptions/daylight operations and are best used for the major-region prong rather than a complete listed-airport suspension theory.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search ledger and weight assessment\\nDefendant reviewed the current evidence list and read plaintiff's three new submitted captures. Targeted searches used exact terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OITR OIKK, western Tehran FIR, and CAO denial language. Defendant found and submitted a Notamify raw NOTAM mirror and an Iran International contemporaneous denial/limitation report. No direct official Iranian aviation authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. Weight assessment: the raw mirror is probative but not official custody; it supports timing/formality while narrowing scope to airport/aerodrome closures with exceptions. The Iran International report does not negate the western airport suspension but conflicts with any broader countrywide or airspace-wide characterization.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal scope analysis\\nDefendant's evidence was read in full. The Notamify mirror confirms formal NOTAM A1010/26, May 22-May 25 timing, closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except limited daylight airports, suspension of all prior permissions for all operators, and a new CAA permission requirement for civil IFR passenger flights. Iran International denies a new countrywide airspace notice but confirms the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension. Rebuttal therefore focuses on the market rule's major-region language rather than the listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nDefendant inspected the record after plaintiff rebuttal. Plaintiff added no new source material and relied on defendant's existing D-X1/D-X2 exhibits. No additional outside source was needed because the rebuttal issue is the legal and evidentiary weight of the existing raw NOTAM mirror and Iran International scope report. The unresolved gap remains direct official-source custody and proof that the airport/aerodrome notice closed transiting commercial airspace or completely suspended listed-airport arrivals/departures.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":891996,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":21}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C3","after_version":21,"case_id":"arb-ex12-20260630145920","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C3","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C3\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it must be proven with discipline. The proposition is not whether air travel around Iran became risky, whether airlines avoided Iran, or whether foreign states issued warnings. The proposition is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a qualifying, major, non-weather closure of Iranian airspace under this market’s rule.\n\nThe current case packet already fixes the legal test. The market-page record defines a qualifying closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately provides that a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports can qualify. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Limited cancellations, delays, airline-specific choices, foreign warnings, weather closures, or narrow partial restrictions do not decide this market.\n\nThat framing matters because it tells the council what evidence should count most. The rule identifies the primary resolution sources as official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files candidly state that no merits packet has yet been built. They point us to the same source classes that should decide the case: Iranian Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority records, public NOTAM material if available and attributable, airport-level operations records for the listed airports, and credible contemporaneous reporting that distinguishes an Iran-imposed commercial closure from airline rerouting, foreign restrictions, weather, or military-drill limits. Flight-tracking observations may corroborate operational effect, but they cannot by themselves prove who initiated the restriction or why.\n\nThe plaintiff’s theory is that the decisive evidence will show an Iranian-authority restriction, in force before the cutoff, that was imposed for non-weather security or military-tension reasons and was broad enough to satisfy the rule’s “major Iranian airspace region” or listed-airport standard. If official NOTAM or aviation-authority material shows that Iran suspended civilian or commercial flight permissions across a major portion of the Tehran FIR, and if credible reporting or airport records show that this affected commercial arrivals and departures at at least two covered airports before the deadline, the preponderance standard is met.\n\nThe present packet also identifies the main gaps and the likely defense. The unresolved-gaps file notes that the record does not yet preserve the relevant NOTAMs, official aviation notices, airport operation records, contemporaneous reporting, UMA rationales, or exact ET timing. It also flags the possibility that observed flight effects could have been caused by airlines or foreign governments rather than Iran, or that a restriction could have been too limited, regional, or exception-filled to qualify. Those are real weight issues. They do not defeat the plaintiff’s case at the opening stage, but they define the proof plaintiff must bring in the evidence phases.\n\nSo the council should evaluate this case by asking five questions. First, is there an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act? Second, was it in force no later than May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET? Third, was the cause non-weather? Fourth, did it suspend or close commercial operations broadly enough across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two listed airports? Fifth, do official records and credible reporting corroborate the same account rather than merely repeating market chatter?\n\nPlaintiff expects to answer those questions with admitted source material, not speculation. The record already gives the rule, the burden, and the source hierarchy. The missing merits materials should be obtained and admitted next. If those materials show only a narrow, airline-specific, foreign-imposed, weather-related, or post-deadline disruption, plaintiff will not have carried the burden. But if they show an Iran-issued, non-weather NOTAM or equivalent official restriction that materially suspended commercial operations in the covered way before the cutoff, then the proposition is more likely true than not and the market should resolve for plaintiff.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the record presently proves the rule, not the proposition.\n\nThe proposition is not whether Iran was tense, whether traders expected disruption, whether aircraft rerouted, or whether some aviation notice may have existed. It is whether, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure under this market's specific rule. Plaintiff bears that burden by a preponderance.\n\nThe case-packet evidence narrows the dispute. The market-page file defines a qualifying event as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also allows a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. But the same rule excludes limited cancellations, delays, other partial closures, airline or foreign-government restrictions, and weather closures. Limited exceptions to a broad closure may be tolerated, but that does not erase the plaintiff's need to prove breadth, attribution, timing, and non-weather cause.\n\nThe other packet files are even more important for weight. The official-source-record, primary-evidence, and secondary-reporting files all tell us that no merits packet has yet been built. They do not contain an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization announcement, an authenticated NOTAM, airport operations records, a Reuters-style merits report about May 24, or a consensus of credible contemporaneous reporting. The unresolved-record-gaps file expressly says the packet does not yet preserve the relevant Iranian aviation records, NOTAMs, airport records, reporting, UMA rationales, source event, causation analysis, breadth analysis, or exact ET timing.\n\nThat is not a technicality. Those missing links are the case. Flight-tracking patterns could show operational disruption, but they do not by themselves prove who initiated it. News or social-media claims could locate a lead, but they do not by themselves prove the exact notice, its legal effect, its exceptions, its airport coverage, or whether it was a countrywide, major-region, or merely limited regional restriction. Even an Iranian notice would still need to be read carefully: a western-sector restriction, daylight-only operating rule, requirement for fresh permissions, military-drill notice, VFR/general-aviation suspension, or airport-specific measure may be materially different from the market's required major commercial-airspace closure.\n\nThe council should therefore ask plaintiff to prove five things with admitted source material, not inference from market movement: first, an attributable Iranian aviation-authority act; second, effectiveness no later than the May 24 ET cutoff; third, a non-weather reason; fourth, qualifying breadth under the rule, including whether arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports were completely suspended if plaintiff uses the airport prong; and fifth, corroboration from the rule's preferred source hierarchy rather than circular reporting or screenshots of screenshots.\n\nThe defense expects the evidence phases to turn on exact source-chain work: the full NOTAM text if public, official Iranian aviation statements, airport-level operations records, credible reports that distinguish Iran-imposed restrictions from airline or foreign state decisions, and any contrary official statements that conditions remained normal or that no new broad notice existed. Provenance matters because this market's wording is precise and because partial aviation restrictions can look dramatic in headlines while falling short of the rule.\n\nAt this opening stage, the fair conclusion is modest. Plaintiff may later find and admit decisive records. But the current record does not yet establish a qualifying closure. It establishes that the decisive official and corroborating materials are missing, and it preserves several reasons a disruption might not count: wrong actor, wrong scope, wrong airport coverage, wrong timing, weather, exceptions, or partial regional limits. Unless plaintiff fills those gaps with admitted evidence, the proposition should resolve No.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the merits evidence the opening identified as necessary. The proposition should resolve Yes under the preponderance standard.\n\nPX-1 gives the rule. A qualifying closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure. The rule also has a separate listed-airport suspension route, but plaintiff does not need to overstate that route here. The strongest proof is the major-region route: western Tehran FIR.\n\nPX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 all point to the same event. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region. It identifies the source as the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority and the instrument as NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. It further reports that all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR were shut, that only eight airports remained operational under daylight restrictions, and that fresh per-flight Civil Aviation Authority approval was required.\n\nPX-3 independently corroborates the core event. Gulf News reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight specific sites. That matters because it confirms both the government source and the aviation-operational nature of the restriction.\n\nPX-4 supplies the most precise timing and operational detail. It reports that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 was effective from May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30Z. May 22 at 20:46Z is May 22 at 4:46 PM Eastern time, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET cutoff, and the stated end time runs past the cutoff. PX-4 also reports that all prior operator permissions were suspended and that new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at affected airports. It describes the restriction as applying broadly to civil aviation activity in the western Tehran FIR, while preserving limited daylight operations at designated sites.\n\nThose facts satisfy each operative element. First, initiation: the evidence consistently attributes the NOTAM to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Second, timing: the restriction began May 22 and remained valid into May 25, covering the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather: none of the admitted reports describes weather as the cause. The stated context is military and security tension, possible U.S. strikes, operational needs, and the wider Iran conflict. Fourth, major breadth: the western portion of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reports describe closure or restriction of most western airports, suspension of civil flight permits or prior operator permissions, fresh CAA approval for passenger IFR operations, and commercial rerouting.\n\nThe defense is right about one thing: provenance and limits matter. Plaintiff did not capture the official NOTAM itself, and the admitted reports describe exceptions. Some airports remained available in daylight, and the precise list of exceptions is not uniform across all reports. Those limits reduce the force of any argument that every listed airport was completely suspended. They do not defeat the major-region theory. The market rule expressly allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, and it does not require a nationwide closure if the closure applies generally to a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nOn this record, the better reading is that Iran did more than issue a warning or watch airlines make their own choices. Iran's aviation authority imposed a formal NOTAM restriction over western Tehran FIR, suspended existing permissions, required new CAA approvals for passenger operations, and left only limited daylight exceptions. That is an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major regional closure before the deadline. The proposition is therefore more likely true than not.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not pretend nothing happened. The record now shows a serious Iranian aviation restriction from May 22 to May 25. But plaintiff still has not proven the proposition as written: a major closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\n\nStart with what the admitted evidence proves. PX-2, PX-3, and PX-4 are secondary reports saying that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26. They support attribution to Iran, a May 22 start, a non-weather security or operational context, and some real operational restriction in the western part of the Tehran FIR. D-X1, the raw NOTAM text as displayed by Notamify, largely confirms the timing and the core wording.\n\nBut D-X1 also shows the central limit. The raw Q-line is OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999, and the operative text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights on these airports. That is an airport/aerodrome closure notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice saying the Tehran FIR airspace, western Tehran FIR airspace, or transiting commercial routes were closed. The distinction matters because the market rule does not count every partial restriction. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports.\n\nPlaintiff's listed-airport route fails on this record. The listed airports are IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. D-X1's raw exception list names OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW; among the listed market airports, only OISS/SYZ appears there. PX-2, by contrast, says IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN were among the airports that remained operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. Either way, plaintiff has not shown a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. The source list is internally inconsistent, and no airport operations records have been submitted.\n\nPlaintiff therefore relies on the major-region theory. That theory is closer, but the burden still matters. The best raw text in evidence speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not closure of the FIR's airspace. It preserves eight daylight exceptions and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA approval. PX-3 describes the measure as restrictions at most western airports and notes limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 calls it portions of airspace and affected airports, but again admits designated daylight operations. PX-2 is further downstream: it attributes key NOTAM details to Gulf News and does not reproduce the official NOTAM.\n\nD-X2 adds a contemporaneous conflict. Iran International reported that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flights were operating according to plan. That report also acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, so it does not erase D-X1. It does, however, undercut plaintiff's effort to turn an airport-specific western restriction into a proved countrywide or airspace-wide closure.\n\nProvenance also remains weak for a market whose rule names official Iranian aviation information as a primary source. Plaintiff candidly admits no official NOTAM database record or Iranian authority page was captured. D-X1 is a mirror, not the official source. The council can use it, but should give care to what it actually says: airport closures in part of a FIR, exceptions, daylight operations, and approval requirements.\n\nUnder a preponderance standard, this record proves a limited but serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not more likely than not prove the rule's qualifying major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the proposition. It confirms the core plaintiff case.\n\nPX-R1, defendant’s Notamify raw-NOTAM mirror, is now the closest thing in the record to the NOTAM text. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 EST/estimated. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating only from sunrise to sunset. Most importantly, it says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\n\nThat is not merely an airline choice, foreign warning, or market rumor. It is a formal Iranian CAA permission regime for civil passenger operations in the west part of the Tehran FIR, in force across the market deadline. That proves Iran initiation, timing, and commercial-flight effect more directly than plaintiff’s secondary reports alone did.\n\nDefendant’s scope argument asks the council to read the rule too narrowly. The rule is not limited to an enroute-only FIR closure. It covers a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Airport closures across the west part of Tehran FIR, plus suspension of all prior operator permissions and new CAA approval for civil IFR passenger flights, are a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that major region. The rule also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. The eight daylight exceptions therefore prove breadth with exceptions; they do not erase the closure.\n\nPlaintiff does not need the separate listed-airport complete-suspension prong. Defendant spends time showing uncertainty about IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. That would matter if plaintiff’s only theory were complete suspension at two listed airports. It is not. The major-region prong independently resolves the case.\n\nPX-R2 also helps plaintiff once read carefully. Iran International reports a denial of a new notice limiting flights across the country. But it also states that the denial came after Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization said activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise to sunset. So PX-R2 rebuts a countrywide-overclaim; it does not rebut the western-FIR closure that satisfies the market’s major-region language.\n\nThe record now has consistent secondary reporting, defendant’s raw NOTAM mirror, and even defendant’s denial article acknowledging the earlier western-FIR suspension. The official-source gap affects weight, but the preponderance is clear: before the cutoff, Iran imposed a non-weather CAA restriction that broadly suspended civil passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR, with limited exceptions. That is a qualifying major closure under the rule.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff's rebuttal fairly identifies the strongest point for Yes: D-X1 proves a formal CAA permission regime for civil IFR passenger operations at western Tehran FIR airports. The defense accepts that. The remaining question is whether that equals the market rule's qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nIt does not, at least not by a preponderance on this record. The rule's limited-exception sentence matters only after plaintiff proves an otherwise broad closure. It does not make every airport restriction with exceptions into a closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nD-X1's exact wording is narrower than plaintiff's characterization. The Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope, and the E-line says \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" except eight named airports. It then says new CAA permission is needed for civil IFR passenger flights \"on these airports.\" That is airport/aerodrome language. The record still lacks a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, barring commercial overflights, or suspending commercial flights transiting through the region.\n\nPlaintiff now disclaims reliance on the listed-airport prong, and rightly so: the record does not show complete suspension of arrivals and departures at two listed airports. That leaves only the major-region theory. But the evidence for that theory is still a mirror of an airport notice plus secondary reports. There are no airport operations records, no official Iranian authority page, no official NOTAM database capture, and no direct flight-permission dataset showing region-wide commercial suspension.\n\nD-X2 also matters in the narrow way the defense offered it. It acknowledges an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension, but reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions. That is not a knockout, but it is a warning against inflating a western airport-notice record into a broader airspace-closure finding.\n\nSo the record proves a serious, Iran-issued, non-weather airport restriction before the deadline. It does not prove the rule's major closure of Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The preponderance remains with No.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the closing question is not whether the record is perfect. It is whether the proposition is more likely true than not. It is.\n\nThe rule asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. The rule defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure. That language is decisive.\n\nThe strongest evidence is now defendant’s own raw NOTAM mirror. It confirms NOTAM A1010/26, effective May 22 at 20:46Z until May 25 at 08:30 estimated. That period begins before the deadline and extends beyond it. The text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except eight named airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then says all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and new permission had to be requested from CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\n\nThat proves the essential points. The actor was Iran’s aviation authority: a CAA permission requirement imposed through a NOTAM. The timing was before and through the market cutoff. The cause was non-weather: the record places it in a security, military, and operational context, and no evidence suggests weather. The effect was major: across the west part of the Tehran FIR, all airports were closed except limited daylight exceptions, prior permissions were canceled for all operators, and civil passenger IFR operations required new CAA permission.\n\nDefense’s best point is that the NOTAM is framed as an airport or aerodrome closure, not an enroute FIR closure. But the market rule is broader than that. It does not require a pure overflight ban. It covers broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Commercial passenger flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except narrow daylight exceptions, and all prior permissions for civil IFR passenger operations are suspended pending fresh CAA approval, commercial flight operations in that major region have been broadly suspended.\n\nThe listed-airport prong is not necessary. Plaintiff need not prove complete suspension at two named airports because the major-region prong independently covers this record. Defense’s focus on IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN therefore does not answer the core proof.\n\nNor does the Iran International article defeat the case. It denies a new countrywide airspace notice and reports normal conditions in that broader sense. But it also acknowledges the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension until Monday with limited sunrise-to-sunset operations. That is exactly why plaintiff has not argued a countrywide closure. The proposition is satisfied by a major Iranian airspace region, and the west part of Tehran FIR qualifies on this record.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the provenance limits: no official database capture was admitted, and Notamify is a mirror. But the mirror preserves raw NOTAM text, the secondary reports consistently corroborate it, and even the defense’s adverse report confirms the earlier western-FIR suspension. Against that, defense offers a narrower legal characterization, not a better factual explanation.\n\nBy a preponderance, Iran initiated a formal, non-weather, CAA-controlled suspension of civil passenger flight operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR before the cutoff, with only limited exceptions. Under the market’s own text, that is a major closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should decide Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is not that the May 22-25 measure was trivial. It was serious. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market proposition: a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace, within the rule, by the cutoff.\n\nThe record proves several points for plaintiff. D-X1 confirms a NOTAM-like text, A1010/26, effective before and through the cutoff. It connects the measure to Iran's CAA and a non-weather security or operational context. It shows real restrictions on civil IFR passenger operations at airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR. Those points should be accepted.\n\nBut they are not enough. The market rule is precise. A qualifying major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Separately, a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports qualifies. Plaintiff has abandoned the listed-airport route, and the record would not support it anyway: there is no operations record showing complete suspension at two listed airports, and the secondary reports conflict on which airports remained operational.\n\nSo everything turns on the major-region route. The best evidence for that route is D-X1, and D-X1 says something narrower than plaintiff needs. Its Q-line is QFALC with an /A/ scope. Its operative text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except eight named airports operating sunrise to sunset. It then requires new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is an airport/aerodrome notice with exceptions. It is not a captured official notice closing western Tehran FIR airspace, suspending commercial overflights, or barring flights transiting the region.\n\nPlaintiff's closing says commercial flights arrive and depart through airports, so airport closures across a region should be enough. That is the strongest Yes argument. But the rule does not say any broad airport restriction counts. It says commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The word transiting is not surplusage, and the rule separately created a listed-airport prong for airport-specific complete suspensions. Reading an airport/aerodrome notice with daylight exceptions as an airspace closure collapses that distinction.\n\nThe limited-exceptions clause does not solve plaintiff's problem. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure once a broad closure is proven. They do not prove breadth by themselves. Here the exceptions are central: eight airports remained available sunrise to sunset, civil IFR passenger flights could occur with fresh CAA permission, and the evidence never supplies official operations records showing actual region-wide commercial suspension.\n\nProvenance also still matters. The primary source called for by the market is official Iranian aviation information. No official Iranian authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. The raw text is from a mirror. The corroborating reports are secondary, and their airport lists are inconsistent. D-X2 confirms an earlier western airport suspension, but also reports a CAO denial of a new countrywide airspace restriction and normal flight conditions, which counsels against overreading the measure.\n\nOn this record, the fair finding is that Iran imposed a formal, non-weather, western Tehran FIR airport restriction before the deadline. That may be close to the line, but plaintiff had to prove a qualifying major closure of airspace or a major airspace region. The decisive gap remains the same at closing: airport/aerodrome restrictions with exceptions are not proven to be the rule's major airspace closure. The proposition should resolve No.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and operative elements\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource capture: Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". URL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:00Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Headline: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks.\n- Subheadline: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under daylight-only restrictions even as US Secretary of State Marco Rubio, speaking in New Delhi on Saturday, said Washington may have \"something to say\" on a possible Iran deal in the coming days.\n- By Express Global Desk. 6 min read May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST. First published on May 23, 2026 at 09:05 PM IST.\n- The article states that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighed fresh military strikes and mediators sought to revive US-Iran talks.\n- It states that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, attributed to Gulf News.\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational, including Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas; even at those airports flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority according to the NOTAM.\n- It states that flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\n- The article describes the closure as a strong indicator that Tehran expected military action within days, not as a weather event.\n- The article quiz section restates that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region; restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remained valid until May 25, 2026.\n- The quiz section also restates that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas, with daylight-only flights and fresh per-flight CAA approval.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured text extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM itself. The article attributes a key point to Gulf News and refers to the NOTAM but does not reproduce full NOTAM text.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News corroborating live update\nSource capture: Gulf News, live article \"Trump says a deal with Iran and opening of Strait of Hormuz are 'largely negotiated'\". URL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:07:30Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Gulf News Report. Last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29.\n- Live entry timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026.\n- Entry heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\n- The entry states that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\n- The entry explains that NOTAM means Notice to Air Missions, an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\n- The entry states that the move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\n- The entry states that it unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary live news page. It corroborates the existence, source, timing, and broad western-airport nature of the restriction, but does not reproduce the full NOTAM and includes the adverse limitation that limited daytime flights remained at eight sites and that officials cited operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Kenya Times detailed NOTAM timing and effect report\nSource capture: The Kenya Times, \"Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window\". URL: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/ . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:08:00Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Article title: Iran Restricts Airspace as U.S. Signals Imminent Strike Window.\n- Author/date: by Jason Ndunyu, May 23, 2026.\n- The article states that Iran closed portions of its airspace as reports emerged that the United States was preparing for potential military strikes while maintaining diplomatic signaling with Tehran.\n- It states that, according to a newly issued Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), identified as OIIX A1010/26, all airports in the western portion of the Tehran Flight Information Region were closed to operations except for a limited number of facilities operating only during daylight hours.\n- It states that the restriction was effective from Friday, May 22 at 20:46Z until Monday, May 25 at 08:30Z, applied broadly to civil aviation activity, and permitted only designated airports to operate between sunrise and sunset under strict conditions.\n- It states that, according to the NOTAM, all prior operator permissions were suspended and new approvals had to be obtained from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority for IFR passenger operations at the affected airports.\n- It states that the measure affected key regional airports while maintaining limited daytime activity at selected sites, including OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW.\n- It states that, as of May 23, 2026, live Flightradar24 tracking showed a notable disruption in civilian air traffic over and around Iran following reports of the NOTAM, with visible flight paths bending around western, central, and eastern corridors and most aircraft diverting north, south, or further east.\n- It attributes the timing of the restriction to U.S. military and intelligence officials adjusting posture in anticipation of possible developments involving Iran; it describes CBS reporting that the administration was preparing for a fresh round of military strikes but no final decision had been made as of Friday afternoon.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a captured extract of a secondary news article, not the official NOTAM. It provides the most detailed captured wording found in this investigation, including Zulu timing and airport-code exceptions, but plaintiff has not captured the official NOTAM database record itself.\n\n[defendant] D-X1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 mirror showing airport-closure wording and exceptions\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\n\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\n\n[defendant] D-X2 Iran International report on CAO denial and limited western-FIR suspension\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\n\n[defendant] D-X3 Market rule and operative elements\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[defendant] D-X4 Initial unresolved record gaps\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\n- The May 24 market is captured as disputed in the Gamma API, but the packet does not yet preserve the UMA proposal texts or dispute rationales.\n- The packet does not yet identify the event or report that caused the Yes proposal/dispute cycle.\n- The packet does not yet preserve Iranian aviation authority records, NOTAMs, airport operations records, or contemporaneous credible reporting about the May 24 cutoff.\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether observed flight cancellations or route changes, if any, were initiated by Iran rather than airlines or foreign governments.\n- The packet does not yet resolve whether any closure was broad enough to qualify under the market rule, rather than a limited, regional, airline-specific, foreign, military-drill, or weather-related restriction.\n- The packet does not yet resolve exact timing in ET relative to May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defense raw NOTAM mirror confirms west Tehran FIR airport closure and CAA permission regime\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\n\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Iran International report confirms earlier western Tehran FIR suspension while denying new countrywide notice\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\n\n[defendant] D-S1 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-closure wording and exceptions\nSource capture: Notamify public NOTAM page for OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:12:00Z.\n\nRelevant displayed title/summary:\n- All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM as displayed by Notamify:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a NOTAM mirror/display page, not a direct official Iranian aviation authority page. The text is valuable because it preserves raw NOTAM wording, but the official database record itself was not captured. The Q-line includes QFALC and /A/, indicating an aerodrome/airport closure notice rather than a full enroute airspace-closure NOTAM; the E-line speaks of airports in the west part of Tehran FIR, not all airspace routes. The notice contains exceptions and daylight operations for eight named airports.\n\n[defendant] D-S2 Iran International scope-conflict report\nSource capture: Iran International, 'Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country'. URL: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595 . Retrieved 2026-06-30T15:13:00Z.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n- Title: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\n- Timestamp: May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n- The article states that Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- It states that the organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson is quoted: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- The article states that, without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The article adds an important limitation: the denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- It states that the earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\nProvenance/limits: This is a secondary news report, not a direct CAO page. It does not erase the earlier western-FIR airport suspension; instead it creates a conflict about whether there was a new or countrywide airspace restriction and confirms that the earlier measure had named airport exceptions and daylight operations.\n\n[defendant] D-S3 Market rule requiring qualifying major closure\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted). \n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM A1010/26 (ev_09982b77bf9e_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-09982b77bf9e)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `09982b77bf9e0e286f4a48c8acf9eb0a7b045c347babec5f61d3235fa31efa89`\nBytes: 2847\nRelevance: Credible secondary reporting identifying Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, its May 22-May 25 validity, western Tehran FIR scope, remaining operational airports, daylight limits, and per-flight approval requirement.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News live update on Iran western airspace restriction (ev_9f6b49a1ebfa_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-9f6b49a1ebfa)\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\nSHA-256: `9f6b49a1ebfa2299a9bb316abddea1905ad902f9869e311efb954910336e9af0`\nBytes: 1742\nRelevance: Corroborating report that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites and possible military-exercise/security context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Kenya Times report with detailed NOTAM A1010/26 timing and affected airport codes (ev_47df93957e6e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-47df93957e6e)\nSource: https://thekenyatimes.com/middle-east/iran-restricts-airspace/\nSHA-256: `47df93957e6e97187f3df3ccc2010c24353530fc5f9b5c1ae893cbd3a2a132a8`\nBytes: 2445\nRelevance: Secondary report supplying detailed claimed NOTAM timing, airport-code exceptions, civil aviation scope, CAA approval requirement, and flight-tracking corroboration/adverse limits.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 text for OIIX western Tehran FIR airports (ev_342c71021810_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-342c71021810)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `342c71021810e497c6cbdb15471b672347336f282c814a93a94f56d7441f8bff`\nBytes: 1271\nRelevance: Provides the closest captured raw NOTAM wording found in defendant investigation, including NOTAM code, Q-line/aerodrome closure classification, effective period, western Tehran FIR airport closure language, exceptions, sunrise-to-sunset limit, and CAA approval requirement. Relevant to scope and whether the event was a broad airspace closure or airport-specific restriction with exceptions.\n\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: CAO denial of new countrywide NOTAM and normal flight conditions (ev_4c36e105a2b8_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4c36e105a2b8)\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\nSHA-256: `4c36e105a2b8b132be10b9565d835443d0d94971a416c40fea4d60042f9e56a1`\nBytes: 1754\nRelevance: Contemporaneous secondary reporting of an Iranian Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson denial of a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions across the country's airspace, while acknowledging an earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension with limited exceptions. Relevant to conflict, scope, and weight.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search ledger and weight assessment\nPlaintiff searched exact NOTAM and source terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OIIX NOTAM, May 22 western Tehran FIR, Iran CAA/CAO western airspace, and May 24 cutoff terms. No official NOTAM database or Iranian aviation authority page was captured in this opportunity. Three secondary pages were captured and submitted: Indian Express, Gulf News, and Kenya Times. They consistently attribute a May 22-May 25 western Tehran FIR civil aviation restriction to Iran's Civil Aviation Authority. Weight limits: they are secondary; one attributes detail to another source; the full official NOTAM is not in the record; the reports describe exceptions/daylight operations and are best used for the major-region prong rather than a complete listed-airport suspension theory.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search ledger and weight assessment\nDefendant reviewed the current evidence list and read plaintiff's three new submitted captures. Targeted searches used exact terms including OIIX A1010/26, A1010/26 OITR OIKK, western Tehran FIR, and CAO denial language. Defendant found and submitted a Notamify raw NOTAM mirror and an Iran International contemporaneous denial/limitation report. No direct official Iranian aviation authority page or official NOTAM database record was captured. Weight assessment: the raw mirror is probative but not official custody; it supports timing/formality while narrowing scope to airport/aerodrome closures with exceptions. The Iran International report does not negate the western airport suspension but conflicts with any broader countrywide or airspace-wide characterization.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal scope analysis\nDefendant's evidence was read in full. The Notamify mirror confirms formal NOTAM A1010/26, May 22-May 25 timing, closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except limited daylight airports, suspension of all prior permissions for all operators, and a new CAA permission requirement for civil IFR passenger flights. Iran International denies a new countrywide airspace notice but confirms the earlier western Tehran FIR airport suspension. Rebuttal therefore focuses on the market rule's major-region language rather than the listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nDefendant inspected the record after plaintiff rebuttal. Plaintiff added no new source material and relied on defendant's existing D-X1/D-X2 exhibits. No additional outside source was needed because the rebuttal issue is the legal and evidentiary weight of the existing raw NOTAM mirror and Iran International scope report. The unresolved gap remains direct official-source custody and proof that the airport/aerodrome notice closed transiting commercial airspace or completely suspended listed-airport arrivals/departures.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C3","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C3","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":891996,"role_id":"council","turn_number":11},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":21}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782832691852},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9586ebee9f35453d99a5a3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, suspending all civil flight permissions in the western part of the Tehran FIR with new CAA approval required. This constitutes a broad, non-weather, major closure of a major Iranian airspace region, satisfying the rule's major-region prong. The timing, attribution, and operational effect are proven by admitted evidence, even with limited exceptions.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct-2507","usage":{"input":20726,"output":130,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":20856,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782832691858,"responseId":"gen-1782832692-IHwIxzRVQims5Zm984PY"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9586ebee9f35453d99a5a3","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex12-20260630145920\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 889311\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex12-20260630145920\",\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889311,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex12-20260630145920\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 889311\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex12-20260630145920\",\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889311,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex12-20260630145920","member_id":"C3","ok":true,"result":{"text":"Council vote accepted."},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":true,"deadline":"2026-06-30T15:33:03.843932956Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C3","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C3","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889311,"role_id":"council","turn_number":11}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"submit_council_vote"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782832694534},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"My vote has been accepted."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct-2507","usage":{"input":21086,"output":6,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21092,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782832694534,"responseId":"gen-1782832694-cMSsJiebb41UrEZzpF4E"}],"willRetry":false}
